{"source_key":"sha256-2b42e4c8c78d13a2fcd49fac33698d97","record_index":343,"record_hash":"sha256:cef263cc49c24d89401096220ee003229d8b97d123ac223897f17e3c169ecf47","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:14.468Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: ff41ef\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1974\nOutput:\n     1\t# Agent Trail\n     2\t\n     3\tAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\n     4\tIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\n     5\tbehind a change.\n     6\t\n     7\t## Working Name\n     8\t\n     9\tUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n    10\t\n    11\tGood PR link text:\n    12\t\n    13\t- View Agent Trail\n    14\t- Explore Agent Trail\n    15\t- Agent Trail for this PR\n    16\t\n    17\tAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\n    18\tproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\n    19\tbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\n    20\tchange.\n    21\t\n    22\t## Product Shape\n    23\t\n    24\tFor v1, a reviewer starts from a GitHub pull request URL and opens the matching\n    25\tGitButler-owned Agent Trail URL by replacing the host. The server builds or\n    26\tloads a generated snapshot for that public pull request.\n    27\t\n    28\tExplicit PR description links, bot comments, check-run details links, or GitHub\n    29\tapp panels can come later as distribution channels. They are not required for\n    30\tthe first build.\n    31\t\n    32\tThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\n    33\trequest:\n    34\t\n    35\t- prompts and requests from the human\n    36\t- assistant responses and claims\n    37\t- tool calls and tool results\n    38\t- tests and validation attempts\n    39\t- decisions and tradeoffs\n    40\t- follow-up questions\n    41\t- edge cases discussed or missed\n    42\t\n    43\tThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\n    44\ttruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\n    45\tunderstand the change.\n    46\t\n    47\t## Core Question\n    48\t\n    49\tAgent Trail should answer:\n    50\t\n    51\t> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n    52\t\n    53\t\n[TRUNCATED]\n151\tbranch target: ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>\n   152\t```\n   153\t\n   154\tCurrent preference: search both when PR metadata is already available, then rank\n   155\treview-target hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub PR lookup fails, v1 should\n   156\tfail closed with a retryable error state instead of guessing from GitMeta alone.\n   157\t\n   158\tBranch fallback is useful but weaker. A branch can be reused, renamed, or shared\n   159\tacross unrelated work. The UI should show why each session matched and avoid\n   160\ttreating branch-only matches as proof that the session belongs to the PR.\n   161\tBranch-only matches should be visually separated from review-target matches and\n   162\traw record drill-down for branch-only matches should require an explicit expand.\n   163\t\n   164\tChange target lookup is not relevant for the MVP. It can be considered later if\n   165\tAgent Trail needs a deeper GitButler-specific view of stacked changes.\n   166\t\n   167\tThe first version should focus on public/open-source repositories. Private\n   168\trepository access, GitHub OAuth, GitButler workspace access, and explicit share\n   169\tlinks can come later.\n   170\t\n   171\tFor public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as\n   172\talready published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to\n   173\tprivate data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable\n   174\twithout credentials.\n   175\t\n   176\tThis entry point should show one of:\n   177\t\n   178\t- an existing generated snapshot\n   179\t- a newly generated review-safe overview, if access and policy allow it\n   180\t- a clear \"no trail available\" state\n   181\t\n   182\tOn-demand generation is attractive because it avoids needing every PR to be\n   183\tpre-linked by GitButler. It also gives reviewers a memorable gesture: replace\n   184\tthe forge domain with the Agent Trail domain.\n   185\t\n   186\t## Data Source\n   187\t\n   188\tAgent Trail should build on `but-agentlog` primitives:\n   189\t\n   190\t- durable project-scoped agent sessions\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:14.468Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}